description: Served as an Intelligence Sergeant within III Corps, G2 Operations Section. Responsible for planning, implementing and supervising training for 34 Soldiers. title: Threat Finance Targeting Analyst
description: Afghanistan Threat Finance Cell Liaison Officer for Counter Threat Finance Analysis and Targeting to 1 BDE, 101 INF DIV and 3 BDE, 25 INF DIV. Conducted analysis and coordination of insurgent threat financiers resulting in eight successful additions to the Joint Prioritized Effects List (JPEL), and the capture of two threat finance related High Value Targets (HVTs). Identified a major insurgent finance and drug trafficking hub, and brought the resources of multiple U.S. Government and international agencies to bear on the problem. Received a Joint Service Achievement Medal for providing real-time support to Special Operations Forces, who successfully captured a threat finance HVT. Developed four regional network assessments, which facilitated in the Brigade Combat Team's ability to identify and prosecute multiple networks within the Task Force's Area of Operations. Mentored eight Soldiers and held daily training sessions on effective writing, and briefing techniques, and analytical tools and methods such as M3, Query Tree, Pathfinder, Tripwire (TAC), Analyst’s Notebook, and Firetruck.

title: Intelligence Analyst/Current Operations Specialist
description: Regulated the collection, assembly, and dissemination of Intelligence Information Reports well as force protection-oriented reports to national level agencies and throughout the intelligence community. In addition to reports processing, served in the Operations & Training Section to provide cognitive task analysis in support of collective training plans and devised and implemented resultant training, with the appropriate guidelines and procedures in order to facilitate proper execution. Provided significant input to senior mission leaders regarding unit/collective training assessments as well as assessments in support of individual training strategies towards near and long-term professional development of assigned personnel.

title: Deputy, ISR Futures & Advocacy Assessments Branch
description: Assigned to USSTRATCOM's functional component for global ISR, analyzing future space-based ISR architecture requirements and current system collection accomplishment. Successfully advocated for $5B Space Fence Capabilities Development Document (CDD) and FY15 POM funding, keeping program on-track for FY18 Initial Operational Capability (IOC). Conducted STRATCOM-directed Capabilities-Based Assessment (CBA) of persistent ISR in denied areas, laying groundwork for FY16-20 Integrated Priority List (IPL) nomination and entry into the Joint Capabilities Integration & Development System (JCIDS) process. Developed methodology for first annual assessment of Operational Responsive Space-1 (ORS-1) collection accomplishment and intelligence requirements satisfaction by comparing rates with NTM, theater airborne, and commercial bonusing satisfaction rates. Established a detailed prioritization scheme to schedule and deconflict a diverse set of intelligence collection elements, leading to successful operations against critical combatant command targets, and resulting in an Intelligence Integration Unit Citation from the Office of the Director of National Intelligence (ODNI). Completed the Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA) Special Access Program (SAP) Collection Manager’s Course and Enterprise Collection Management Certification Exam, as well as the US Army Logistics University Capabilities Development Course.

title: Chief, Space Control Branch, Unified Space Vault
description: Led branch of 18 military space operators in performing command & control (C2) of offensive counterspace operations at the Joint Space Operations Center (JSpOC). Developed tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs) for space force C2, including stand-up of Mission Director (MD) crew position and training pipeline. Led three deployed theater coordination elements responsible for integrating counterspace effects and Special Technical Operations (STO) into operational-level planning in direct support of Joint Force Air Component Commander (JFACC) Air Tasking Order execution. Successfully completed the first of several Navigation Warfare (NAVWAR) tests, demonstrations and exercises to maximum protection of warfighter GPS capabilities, preventing its use by the enemy and integrating future weapons capabilities. Partnered with government and industry to develop C2 architecture for the Geosynchronous Space Situational Awareness (GEO SSA) system.

title: Current Operations Flight Commander
description: Led flight of 12 military, civilian, and contractor personnel responsible for operations training, information/personnel security, crisis action management, and engineering design and fabrication across the 30th Operations Group and the 30th Space Wing. Supervised Operations Group training program supplying trained operators for 13 launches worth $3.9B. Led squadron preparations for 2009 14th Air Force Standardization, Evaluation, & Training inspection, resulting in second consecutive "Outstanding" rating for the 30th Operations Group across 4 inspection areas. Incorporated lessons learned from a 617-acre base wildfire and real-world boating accident to develop a $52.5K Crisis Action Team modernization effort to enhance the installation commander's situational awareness and C2. Directly oversaw the redesign and installation of 680 airfield centerline caps, mitigating safety hazards and ensuring base readiness for landing and recovery of the $1B X-37B Orbital Text Vehicle. Named squadron Company Grade Officer of the Year for 2009.

title: Chief, Operations Group Training
description: Lead operations instructor within 30th Operations Group. Developed, managed, and executed instructor training curricula in accordance with Air Force Instructional System Development (ISD) principles and guidance. Trained and certified 31 weapon system instructors from various crew positions across the 30th Operations Group. Certified over 120 training products for use in training 64 Combat Mission Ready (CMR) and Mission Support (MS) operators, directly supporting 13 launches worth $3.9B. Named Air Force Space Command (AFSPC) Instructor of the Year (Cat II) for 2009.

title: Battle Captain
description: Flawlessly executed over 750 intra-theater & international security missions across 6 MNF-I battle spaces in direct support of senior Iraqi Government leadership, including the President, Vice Presidents, Prime Minister, and Speaker of the Council of Representatives. Utilized commercial and military friendly-force tracking systems to sustain real-time situational awareness of convoy operations. Executed Tactical Control (TACON) of US Army Quick Response Force (QRF) to maximize convoy security and assure reliable communications. Directed UAV surveillance operations for top-priority diplomatic missions, including first-ever meetings with Iraqi leadership by the Turkish Prime Minister and the King of Jordan. Named #1 of 13 Joint Expeditionary Tasking (JET) teams in Iraq for July 2008.

title: Range Operations Commander Instructor
description: Led range team of 250+ military and civilian operators in support of 4 space launch and ballistic missile test missions worth over $250M, working closely with mission partners such as NASA, Orbital Sciences, United Launch Alliance (ULA), and the Missile Defense Agency (MDA). Oversaw initial and upgrade Combat Mission Ready training program, delivering over 130 hours of classroom and scenario performance training, and updating 350 training documents in support of all-new Range Operations Manual publication. Led squadron preparations for 2007 14th Air Force Standardization, Evaluation, & Training inspection, resulting in "Outstanding" rating for the 30th Operations Group across 4 inspection areas. Hand-picked to work with government and industry mission partners in developing base landing and recovery procedures for the inaugural X-37Orbital Test Vehicle mission.

title: Intercontinental Ballistic Missile (ICBM) Combat Crew Commander
description: Defended the United States by standing ready to launch up to 50 nuclear-armed ICBMs against strategic targets in response to authenticated nuclear launch commands issued by the President of the United States. As a Squadron Command Post (SCP)-certified crew commander, led the squadron in processing 42 targeting & flight plan updates, directly contributing to the wing's 99.82% missile alert rate in 2005 - the best alert rate achieved in Minuteman history. Oversaw installation of $1.8M force direction system at two Missile Alert Facilities (MAFs) - largest strategic communications upgrade in 10 years. Operational Risk Management (ORM) and Weapons System Safety Programs key to squadron winning Air Force Space Command Unit Safety Award for 2004.

title: Design Engineer (Fire & Gas)
description: • Design and Implementation of the complete Fire Alarm and Gas detection System. • Replying to RFI’s and comments as part of clarifications in design. • Battery Calculation and Voltage Drop Calculations using proper software if required. • Design Fire detection system, Voice evacuation, ASD based on NFPA72 / BS5839. • Well versed with Notifier Fire detection system, Gent Fire Alarm system and Variodyn D1 system. • Reply to the Client Comments, revision of drawings and preparation on Bill of Materials. • Site visit Check List & Report Detailed Design Drawings for Instruments and F & G Instrument & Loop & Signal Diagram, Instrument Support & Installation, Layout, Routing, Wiring Diagram, impulse drawings, termination drawings, Cause & Effect Matrix, MCT, Etc, • Fire & Gas cause and effect matrix chart preparation ESD cause and effect matrix chart preparation. • Training and providing tech support to during time of commissioning and maintenance. • Verify and test all new products/software releases locally prior to release in the region and ensure that all training programs are updated to reflect the latest product lines. • Conduct product training for design team on Security and Fire detection system. • Meeting with client to know specific product and design requirement. • Create data base for product from different vendors. • Ensure part number are updated in central data base. • Create pricing for the product to evaluate approx project cost. • Ensure all product data in the system are updated correctly. • Translate client and/or project team functional requirements into accurate, effective and sustainable technical solutions that meet client needs and drive benefit. • Experience working with SFDC and Oracle. • Understand, analyze and specify customer needs and requirements and work in collaboration with Solutions Architects to design customized solutions.

title: Design and Estimation engineer - Fire and Security
description: • Designing of low voltage systems i.e. Notifier Fire Alarm systems including Addressable fire alarm systems & Conventional fire alarm systems, Voice Evacuation, as per project requirements. • Providing tech support to the on site installation and Commissioning team. • Project and design engineer performing fire detection design, specifications, calculations and design for projects like Joint Operation Wafra ( Kuwait ) for Hazardous areas . UL/C-UL - Class I Division 1, Groups B, C and D, Class I Division 2, Groups B, C & D, Class II Division 1, Groups E, F & G, Class II Division 2, Groups F & G for Toxic (H2S) Gas detection. • Prepare basis of Design, Control Philosophy, Cause and Effect Matrix, Electrical Schematic Diagrams, Control Room Layout, etc. for Detection of Combustible and toxic gases. • Preparation of Technical specifications & Estimation in accordance to the project requirements. • Reply to the Client Comments and revision of drawings and preparation on Bill of Materials.
